%F A002411 G.f.: x*(1+2*x)/(1-x)^4. - _Simon Plouffe_ in his 1992 dissertation
%F A002411 a(n) = n*Sum_{k=0..n} (n-k) = n*Sum_{k=0..n} k. - _Paul Barry_, Jul 21 2003
%F A002411 a(n) = n*A000217(n). - Xavier Acloque, Oct 27 2003
%F A002411 a(n) = (1/2)*Sum_{j=1..n} Sum_{i=1..n} (i+j) = (1/2)*(n^2+n^3) = (1/2)*A011379(n). - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Apr 13 2006
%F A002411 Row sums of triangle A127739, triangle A132118; and binomial transform of [1, 5, 7, 3, 0, 0, 0, ...] = (1, 6, 18, 40, 75, ...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Aug 10 2007
%F A002411 G.f.: x*F(2,3;1;x). - _Paul Barry_, Sep 18 2008
%F A002411 Sum_{j>=1} 1/a(j) = hypergeom([1, 1, 1], [2, 3], 1) = -2 + 2*zeta(2) = A195055 - 2. - _Stephen Crowley_, Jun 28 2009
%F A002411 a(n) = 4*a(n-1) - 6*a(n-2) + 4*a(n-3) - a(n-4); a(0)=0, a(1)=1, a(2)=6, a(3)=18. - _Harvey P. Dale_, Oct 20 2011
%F A002411 From _Ant King_, Oct 23 2012: (Start)
%F A002411 a(n) = 3*a(n-1) - 3*a(n-2) + a(n-3) + 3.
%F A002411 a(n) = (n+1)*(2*A000326(n)+n)/6 = A000292(n) + 2*A000292(n-1).
%F A002411 a(n) = A000330(n)+A000292(n-1) = A000217(n) + 3*A000292(n-1).
%F A002411 a(n) = binomial(n+2,3) + 2*binomial(n+1,3).
%F A002411 (End)
%F A002411 a(n) = (A000330(n) + A002412(n))/2 = (A000292(n) + A002413(n))/2. - _Omar E. Pol_, Jan 11 2013
%F A002411 a(n) = (24/(n+3)!)*Sum_{j=0..n} (-1)^(n-j)*binomial(n,j)*j^(n+3). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Jun 04 2013
%F A002411 Sum_{n>=1} a(n)/n! = (7/2)*exp(1). - _Richard R. Forberg_, Jul 15 2013
%F A002411 E.g.f.: x*(2 + 4*x + x^2)*exp(x)/2. - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, May 31 2016
%F A002411 From _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 28 2016: (Start)
%F A002411 a(n) = A057145(n+4,n).
%F A002411 a(n) = A080851(3,n-1). (End)
%F A002411 For n >= 1, a(n) = (Sum_{i=1..n} i^2) + Sum_{i=0..n-1} i^2*((i+n) mod 2). - _Paolo Xausa_, Apr 13 2021
%F A002411 a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} GCD(k,n) * LCM(k,n). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 22 2021
%F A002411 Sum_{n>=1} (-1)^(n+1)/a(n) = 2 + Pi^2/6 - 4*log(2). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jan 03 2022
%e A002411 a(3)=18 because 4 identical balls can be put into m=2 of n=4 distinguishable boxes in binomial(4,2)*(2!/(1!*1!) + 2!/2!) = 6*(2+1) = 18 ways. The m=2 part partitions of 4, namely (1,3) and (2,2), specify the filling of each of the 6 possible two-box choices. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Nov 13 2007
